> One solution would be for `disconnect` to look up the entry in `signal_map` itself, and check whether it is a persistent entry. Only if `_disconnect` returns true, AND it was a persistent entry, the change signal should be fired.
 
This requires `Node::disconnect` to access the private member `signal_data` from `Object`, I'd need to friend class it or add another function to `Object` to do so. I'm assuming that's not desired. `Object::_disconnect` was only `protected`, so on the original suggestion while I was squeamish about using something with an underscore prefix outside the class itself, friend classing wasn't needed.

> The other solution would be to return `Pair<bool, int>` of `{ was_removed, flags }` from `_disconnect`, where `flags` is the `flags` of the removed `SignalData` (if removed).

I guessed that this would add extra instructions to disconnects in non-editor builds, which I was trying to avoid, since adding instructions to non-editor builds to fix an editor only problem felt bad. The return from `_disconnect` is actually used in non-editor code, so I didn't trust the compiler to be smart enough to realize at link time that it could make a better version with no return to use for some cases, or to inline the whole thing since it's so large. That said, boy howdy does link time optimization take a long time on my builds, and I'm not nearly as familiar with its limits, so hey, maybe it's taking all that time to be super smart.

