I tried to merge this into my Godot fork and ran into the captured-cursor behavior you mention at the end of the description. In my case it was not benign: it broke editor value drags and 3D viewport freelook.

The cause is the synthetic motion event added in `_set_mouse_mode_impl` when the mouse is captured:

```
mm->set_relative(Vector2(mm->get_position() - Vector2(old_x, old_y)));
mm->set_relative_screen_position(mm->get_relative());
old_x = mm->get_position().x;
old_y = mm->get_position().y;

mm->set_position(center);
```
`set_position(center)` runs after `set_relative`, so `mm->get_position()` is still `(0, 0)` on that line. The relative ends up as `(0, 0) - (old_x, old_y)`, the negated previous cursor position, which is a large delta on the first captured frame.

The cursor position blip is invisible while captured, like you noted. The part that bites is that captured-mode consumers read the relative motion, not the position. So an `EditorSpinSlider/SpinBox` drag jumps straight to its min or max, and the editor freelook camera snaps fully up or down the instant the drag starts.

The warp to the window center is a programmatic move, not real input, so the relative should be zero. This is what fixed it for me:

```
mm->set_position(center);
mm->set_global_position(center);
mm->set_relative(Vector2(0, 0));
mm->set_relative_screen_position(Vector2(0, 0));
mm->set_velocity(Vector2(0, 0));
mm->set_screen_velocity(Vector2(0, 0));

old_x = center.x;
old_y = center.y;
```
Resetting `old_x/old_y` to the center also gives the `MOUSE_MOVE_ABSOLUTE` branch in `process_raw_input()` a correct baseline, so absolute-reporting devices start from the center instead of a stale position. After this, drags and freelook start from rest.

@Calinou Ah! Yes, I did have that issue too! The problematic part is the throttled Windows message pump in `process_events()`.

`TranslateMessage()` can post a `WM_CHAR` after a `WM_KEYDOWN`.  `MAX_EVENTS_PER_FRAME_KMB = 1` can dispatch the `WM_KEYDOWN` for `F` in one frame, then leave the generated `WM_CHAR` for the next frame.

Godot’s `_process_key_events()` only ignores that `WM_CHAR` when it is in the same `key_event_buffer` batch as the preceding keydown. If the `WM_CHAR` arrives alone on the next frame, this condition treats it as a fresh pressed key event:

```cpp
if (!KeyMappingWindows::is_extended_key(ke.wParam) && ((i == 0 && ke.uMsg == WM_CHAR) || (i > 0 && key_event_buffer[i - 1].uMsg == WM_CHAR))) {
```

I fixed it by keeping the raw input batching, but restoring normal Windows message queue draining after `process_raw_input()`:

https://github.com/godotengine/godot/blob/9d03a4937bf37c7c5719cbd79d0d94fbe59f0dcf/platform/windows/display_server_windows.cpp#L4235
```cpp
	_THREAD_SAFE_LOCK_

	process_raw_input();

	MSG msg = {};
	while (PeekMessageW(&msg, nullptr, 0, 0, PM_REMOVE)) {
		TranslateMessage(&msg);
		DispatchMessageW(&msg);
	}
	_THREAD_SAFE_UNLOCK_
```

That keeps the generated `WM_CHAR` in the same `_process_key_events()` batch as the `WM_KEYDOWN`, so it gets ignored as intended and `Shift + F` only toggles once.

If this PR still needs to avoid processing `WM_INPUT` through `PeekMessage()`, I think the important rule is: keyboard messages and any `WM_CHAR` generated by `TranslateMessage()` must not be split across frames before `_process_key_events()` runs. Draining all non-`WM_INPUT` messages after `process_raw_input()` should preserve the high-polling raw input benefit without breaking shortcuts.

