I agree that's a weird fix, too. I made some further checks in `PhysicsServer` recently and now I personally believe that there are tons of issues hidden in `GodotSpace2D::test_body_motion`

https://github.com/godotengine/godot/blob/084d5d407e62efcd5be9de44148c5dedce3b9386/modules/godot_physics_2d/godot_space_2d.cpp#L668

As you can see, we are using safe margin in recovery part.

https://github.com/godotengine/godot/blob/084d5d407e62efcd5be9de44148c5dedce3b9386/modules/godot_physics_2d/godot_space_2d.cpp#L798
https://github.com/godotengine/godot/blob/084d5d407e62efcd5be9de44148c5dedce3b9386/modules/godot_physics_2d/godot_space_2d.cpp#L823

But NOT using margin in motion part.

The final result is the summation of both recovery part and motion part, but it does not make sense in a common case: Assuming a body with safe margin which is not overlapping with any obstacle, that is, it won't trigger the recovery part. But if we do a fast enough `test_body_motion` in this case, the body will stick to the wall WITHOUT safe margin. That is, if then we do another `test_body_motion` in next frame, it will surely trigger the recovery motion.

<img width="1152" height="648" alt="recovery_explain" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/eb5dfc09-cd85-4c42-a387-66c0a42771f8" />

#111059 is exactly caused by an unexpected recovery collision report, and I believe even #57706 is in a similar case. Also noticed that I did a lot of tricks in PR #111145, which are mostly related to unexpected recovery collision reports, too.

I guess we should do a slightly fix here, e.g. if a motion collides without triggering recovery collision, then we do a slightly correct on the result so that the margin won't stuck in the wall.

```cpp
if (recovered) {
    r_result->travel += (body_transform.get_origin() - p_parameters.from.get_origin());
} else {
    r_result->travel -= margin * motion_normal; 
}
```

This should be another fix, but I'm not very confident with `PhysicsServer`, not sure if it would make sense in common case.

